Detailed Description

This class is just provided for backward compatibility purposes and may be removed in the future.

Use the EquilStateModel instead which is more general and will continue to be maintained in the future.

Returns a vector of length n_species times n_energies with each corresponding cp per unit mass.

Each n_species vector corresponds to a temperature in the state model. The first one is associated with the heavy particle translational temperature.

◆ getTFromRhoE()

bool getTFromRhoE ( const CpProvider &  cp,
const HProvider &  h,
const double  rhoe,
double &  T,
double *const  p_work,
const double  alpha = 0.0,
const double  atol = 1.0e-12,
const double  rtol = 1.0e-12,
const int  max_iters = 100 
)
inlineprotectedinherited

Solves the general form of an energy equation.

\[ f(T) = T \left[\sum_i \tilde{\rho}_i \left(\frac{H_i(T)}{R_uT}\right) + \alpha\right] - \frac{\rho e}{R_u} = 0 \]

for the temperature given the \(C_{p,i}/R_u\) and \(H_i/R_uT\) function providers using a Newton-Rhapson iterative procedure. This function assumes that the mp_X array is filled with the species molar densities (concentrations) prior to being called. The convergence criteria for the Newton iterations is taken to be

\[ |f(T)| < \epsilon_r\left|\frac{\rho e}{R_u}\right| + \epsilon_a \]

where \(\epsilon_a\) and \(\epsilon_r\) are absolute and relative tolerances respectively. Note that if the total energy equation is being solved, \(\alpha\) should be set to the negative mixture concentration, \(-\sum \tilde{\rho}_i\). For internal energy equations, \(\alpha = 0\).

Parameters
cpclass providing species specific heats
hclass providing species enthalpies
rhoevalue of \(\rho e\)
Tinitial guess on input, output is the solution
p_workwork array, at least number of species long
alphaarbitrary temperature coefficient in energy equation
atolabsolute tolerance, \(\epsilon_a\), on \(f\)
rtolrelative tolerance, \(\epsilon_r\), on \(f\)
max_itersmaximum number of iterations (warns user if exceeded)
Returns
false if max iterations exceeded, true otherwise
